on skill dont increase PA cap...i think. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uubergnome563.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ubergnome563</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/8/02 2:32:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2070.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> if you want to increase your perf cap use a slower weapon of similar dps.  Weaponskill, and in some cases DPS will NOT increase your ideal absolute cap (this being the absolute amount you can hit for if you did 100% of the possible damage.), but it will increase your Minimum. this is ideally how the system of CS / thrust dependancy works (where CS = max, thrust/piercer/otherstuff = min) In reality, since any kinda combat perf involves a standing target (sitting casters = non combat, grays = not included), you never hit this cap anyway, and raising min damage inadvertantly makes you hit harder, which in a twisted way raises your cap against these people.  I'm somewhat skeptical about the thing posted by mythic on weapon specs effecting damage as a % really works given some of the whacky fluctuations in damage i have had.<br>
<br>
If you have a 16.0 dps / 2.2 weapon, and a 15.0 / 3.6 weapon, the 3.6 will perf for more damage because it will hit harder per hit.  <br>
<br>
delay means a lot.  Compare a staff with 9.0 dps and 5.0 delay to something with 14 dps 3.0 delay and see what caps higher (not necessarily hits harder cause of spec).<br>
<br>
You wont be able to do nifty chain stuff like:<br>
<br>
PA<br>
(evade)<br>
CD<br>
SS<br>
Hamstring<br>
Leeper<br>
Rib separation<br>
ripper<br>
garrot<br>
(evade)<br>
hamstring<br>
hamstring<br>
leeper<br>
...<br>
<br>
but you will hit much harder on your perf (which will elimate the need for ninja evade fighting if you one shot them, or take them to like 10% health anyway).<br>
<br>
I've found it more useful to use a lightning fast weapon to perf chain with if i know i cannot one shot them, so i can land CD before they realize I am attacking them, but then again I dont have the 2 handed option, or the LA / shield junk to deal with either.  It may be the tradeoff for having a larger selection of oneshotable targets. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=ebullition>Ebullition</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/8/02 2:38:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2070.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Quickness screwes us again</span><hr size=1> I was able to get my swing time back to were it was before, but my average damage on my styles did decrease some more, and to do it I had to add 15 more Quickness points, which meant I lost some other items.  So I now have 40 points less Hit Points and my strenght is down by 14 points, but at least I can get my reactionary styles to work again.<br>
<br>
I still don't think Quickness is a very good stat, and I would still argue that the slower the Delay and the lower the Quickness the harder the initial hit.<br>
<br>
Strenth gives more weapon skill AND increases carry capacity, while quickness only effects swing speed and our attack speed is capped so at some point quickness is a totally irrelivent stat since you can never swing any faster.<br>
<br>
